PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Rapid Screening Method for Alpha Thalassemia

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Rapid Screening Method for Alpha Thalassemia
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Screening techniques for alpha thalassemia that use melting curve analysis of PCR products generated from the alpha globin alleles.

Concepts.longName: Rapid Screening Method for Alpha Thalassemia
Concepts.definition: Screening techniques for alpha thalassemia that use melting curve analysis of PCR products generated from the alpha globin alleles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A condition in which a person has reduced protein production from one of the four alpha-globin alleles.

Concepts.definition: A condition in which a person has reduced protein production from one of the four alpha-globin alleles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A condition in which a person has reduced protein production from two of the four alpha-globin alleles.

Concepts.definition: A condition in which a person has reduced protein production from two of the four alpha-globin alleles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A heterozygous state in which a person has a mutation in a beta globin allele causing beta thalassemia, together with other structural variants in the other allele.

Concepts.definition: A heterozygous state in which a person has a mutation in a beta globin allele causing beta thalassemia, together with other structural variants in the other allele.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A condition in which a person is heterozygous for a globin gene, with a one normal allele and one defective allele.

Concepts.definition: A condition in which a person is heterozygous for a globin gene, with a one normal allele and one defective allele.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A severe form of alpha thalassemia that results from reduced protein production from three of the four alpha-globin genes. Clinically it is characterized by chronic hemolytic anemia.

Concepts.definition: A form of alpha thalassemia that results from reduced protein production from three of the four alpha-globin genes. Clinically it is characterized by chronic hemolytic anemia.

PermissibleValues.value: Homozygous hemoglobin C or E, non-disease
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Homozygous Hemoglobin C or E, Non-disease

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Homozygous Hemoglobin C or E, Non-disease
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A state in which both beta-globin alleles code for a C or E variant but which leads to such minor changes to the hemoglobin that it does not cause disease.

Concepts.longName: Homozygous Hemoglobin C or E, Non-Disease
Concepts.definition: A state in which both beta-globin alleles code for a C or E variant but which leads to such minor changes to the hemoglobin that it does not cause disease.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A heterozygous state in which a person has a hemoglobin S allele along with a beta-thalassemia allele. The severity of the condition is determined to a large extent by the quantity of normal hemoglobin produced by the beta-thalassemia gene.

Concepts.definition: A heterozygous state in which a person has a hemoglobin S allele along with a beta-thalassemia allele. The severity of the condition is determined to a large extent by the quantity of normal hemoglobin produced by the beta-thalassemia gene.
